  "footnotes": [
    "Herat (Aria / Haroiva): one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world; named in Achaemenid inscriptions as 'Haroiva'; Alexander the Great founded a city here; the Kart dynasty (1244–1389) made it a great Islamic center under Mongol suzerainty; Timurid Herat under Shah Rukh and Gawhar Shad (15th century) was arguably the cultural capital of the Islamic world — a hub of Persian miniature painting, architecture, and poetry",
    "Kandahar (Arachosia / Harauvatī): the name derives from Iskandar (Alexander); Mundigak, 55 km away, is one of the oldest urban sites in South Asia (c.3000 BCE); the Hotak dynasty of Ghilzai Pashtuns was founded here in 1709 — Mirwais Hotak's son Mahmud conquered Isfahan in 1722, ending Safavid rule; Ahmad Shah Durrani founded the Durrani Empire here in 1747, making it the first Afghan capital",
    "Balkh (Bactra): known as 'Umm al-Bilad' (Mother of Cities) in medieval Islamic tradition; possibly the birthplace of Zoroaster; an Achaemenid and Hellenistic capital; the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom ruled from here (250–130 BCE); Genghis Khan destroyed it in 1220 — survivors said the city 'died'; the Uzbek khanates of Bukhara controlled it for most of the early modern period",
    "Kabul (Paropamisadae): the ancient Kabul Valley was the cradle of the Gandhara civilization; Babur, founder of the Mughal Empire, captured Kabul in 1504 and used it as his base; he is buried there; the Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb used it as a summer capital; became the Afghan national capital under Timur Shah Durrani (1776)",
    "Badakhshan: a remote mountainous principality that maintained semi-autonomy through most of history; the world's primary source of lapis lazuli since antiquity, traded as far as Egypt and Mesopotamia; Harappan traders established the colony at Shortugai to control the lapis trade; Marco Polo passed through in 1271 and described its rubies and fine horses",
    "Zunbil dynasty (c.650–870 CE): one of the most remarkable resistance polities in history; Hindu-Buddhist rulers of Zabulistan (between Ghazni and the Helmand) who successfully resisted Arab conquest for over 200 years, defeating multiple Umayyad and early Abbasid campaigns; their patron deity was the sun-god Zun; finally conquered by the Saffarid Ya'qub ibn al-Layth",
    "Hotak dynasty (1709–1738): Mirwais Hotak, a Ghilzai Pashtun tribal chief, launched a successful revolt against the Safavid governor of Kandahar in 1709; his son Shah Mahmud conquered Isfahan in 1722 and ended the Safavid dynasty; the Hotakis ruled Persia until driven out by Nadir Shah (Afsharid) in 1729; the last Hotaki ruler in Kandahar was defeated in 1738",
    "Anglo-Afghan Wars and the Great Game: Britain fought three major wars in Afghanistan (1839–42, 1878–80, 1919) to prevent Russian expansion toward India; the First Anglo-Afghan War ended with the near-total destruction of the British Army of the Indus; the Third ended with Afghan independence in 1919; the competition became known as the 'Great Game' (Rudyard Kipling)"
  ]
}
